{"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"]},"docs":[{"location":"","title":"Home","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"communication/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"communication/existence/","title":"Existence","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"communication/linking/","title":"Linking verbs","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"communication/preference/","title":"Preference","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"communication/semantics/","title":"Semantics","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"conditionals/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"conditionals/antecedent/","title":"Antecedent","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"conditionals/consequent/","title":"Consequent","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"connection/negation/","title":"Negation","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"connection/prepositions/","title":"Prepositions","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"connection/reply/","title":"Replies","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"description/adjectives/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"description/adverbs/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"description/adverbs/derived/","title":"Derived adverbs","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/","title":"Determiners","text":"<p>Determiners are words that precede a noun, providing additional information about which object we are talking about. Arcadia has six types of determiners:</p> <ul> <li>Articles:<ul> <li>Define specificity: the tree, an apple.</li> </ul> </li> <li>Demonstrative determiners:<ul> <li>Indicate proximity: this machine, that person.</li> </ul> </li> <li>Interrogative determiners:<ul> <li>Used in questions: which book, what blanket.</li> </ul> </li> <li>Possessives:<ul> <li>Express ownership: Maria's bag, my bed.</li> </ul> </li> <li>Quantifiers:<ul> <li>Define rough quantities: a few dogs, each child.</li> </ul> </li> <li>Numerals:<ul> <li>Define exact numbers: two dolphins, a million dollars.</li> </ul> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"determiners/#further-details","title":"Further Details","text":"<p>Determiners can be combined when it enhances clarity or adds emphasis, as in \"my three best friends\" or \"the three musketeers.\" In general, nouns in Arcadia require a determiner, unless the noun is inherently specific, such as a proper noun or one in the zero or collective number.</p>"},{"location":"determiners/articles/","title":"Articles","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/demonstratives/","title":"Demonstratives","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/interrogatives/","title":"Interrogatives","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/numerals/","title":"Numerals","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/possessives/","title":"Possessives","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"determiners/quantifiers/","title":"Quantifiers","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/a1/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/a1/good_day/","title":"A good day","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/a1/river/","title":"A walk by the river","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/a2/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"examples/a2/typical_day/","title":"A typical day","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"generation/verbs/","title":"Verbs","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/","title":"Nouns","text":"<p>Nouns form the foundation of any language. In Arcadia, they are classified based on their characteristics and usage.</p> <p>One way to categorize nouns is by specificity:</p> <ul> <li>Proper nouns refer to a unique entity (Arcadia, Maria).</li> <li>Common nouns describe a general concept (tree, apple).</li> </ul> <p>Another categorization is by gender, though Arcadia does not distinguish between masculine, feminine, or neuter nouns. Instead, it uses five grammatical genders, which serve only as structural classifications without semantic meaning. A gender prefix may be used for clarity, but is generally optional.</p> <p>Arcadia also distinguishes nouns by grammatical number. The meaning of each number depends on whether the noun is countable or uncountable.</p> <p>Finally, nouns follow seven cases, which define their role within a sentence.</p>"},{"location":"nouns/cases/","title":"Cases","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/declension/","title":"Declension tables","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/gender/","title":"Gender","text":"<p>Arcadia has five grammatical genders, which serve as structural classifications rather than semantic distinctions. Each gender is named after a prototype noun:</p> <ul> <li>terre (Earth)</li> <li>hidri (Water)</li> <li>fuega (Fire)</li> <li>aero (Air)</li> <li>etheru (Aether)</li> </ul> <p>All nouns in Arcadia end in a vowel, and their gender is determined by the final vowel.</p> <p>However, Arcadia itself is not a gendered language\u2014it does not inherently mark nouns for male or female identity. While gender-specific prefixes exist, they are optional:</p> <ul> <li>\"pa-\" (male)</li> <li>\"ma-\" (female)</li> </ul> <p>When gender is not relevant, the noun remains unmarked.</p> <p>Using Non-Grammatical Gender</p> <p>By default, non-grammatical gender should not be marked unless explicitly relevant. For example, \"datere\" (parent) is used unless specifying \"padatere\" (father) or \"madatere\" (mother).</p>"},{"location":"nouns/gender/#examples","title":"Examples","text":"<ul> <li>Lion \u2192 leona<ul> <li>Male: paleona</li> <li>Female: maleona</li> </ul> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"nouns/number/","title":"Number","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/pronouns/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/pronouns/impersonal/","title":"Impersonal pronouns","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"nouns/pronouns/personal/","title":"Personal pronouns","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"orthography/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"orthography/letters/","title":"Letters","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"orthography/punctuation/","title":"Punctuation","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"verbs/","title":"Index","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"verbs/aspect/","title":"Aspect","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"verbs/category/","title":"Category","text":"<p>\ud83d\udea7 This page is under construction</p>"},{"location":"verbs/declension/","title":"Declension tables","tex